The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton – this summer, readers around the world have held events and bookstores to celebrate the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series, Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (known as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States).
Since his first appearance in 1997, the "boy who would not die" has become a symbol of resilience.
In the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, been translated into over 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight films based on this book have earned a total of $7 billion at the box office, while the Harry Potter merchandise has generated another $7 billion in revenue.
For people of a certain age and with a literary imagination, it's hard to imagine a day when the global audience won't be enchanted by Rowling's works.
So, every time I think back to my students' dreadful reaction to the book "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" in the fall of 1999, I am still astonished, as I had included the book in my popular literature course at Princeton University at the time. I had been teaching the "American Bestsellers" series since 1993.
This course studies popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to ponder why and how these bestsellers have attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I will let the students choose a book representing the latest popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first 'Harry Potter' novel.
In that year, a fierce hurricane hit the coast of the United States.
In June, the American publisher of this series of works rushed to publish the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets".
The institution also published the third installment, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," and a paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" on September 8.
By the end of the month, J.K. Rowling's novels had swept the top three spots on The New York Times bestseller list, while the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" topped the paperback bestseller list.
Time magazine even put this bespectacled wizard on the cover.
Harry Potter's image can be seen everywhere one looks.
My students are eager to know why this craze is happening.
Oh, they were thoroughly disappointed.
To them, the Harry Potter series is nothing but second-rate nonsense that can't even hold a candle to the beloved classics such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings series from their childhood memories.
Despite their childhood being just a few years behind, they have been criticizing "Harry Potter" like many notorious adult critics, saying it is "manipulative", "bad writing", "clichéd" and "boring".
I'm ready to translate.
In their eyes, Harry had neither miracle, nor wit nor warmth.
The students' resentment surprised me at first, but looking back, it didn't seem so remarkable.
Although adults have made up a large part of the Harry Potter audience from the beginning, these students are precisely in the wrong age bracket to objectively recognize the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They were past the age of reading new children's books, but also too young, and didn't yet have their own children (when I had just had my own child),  they were impatiently adamant that despite Harry series being extremely popular now, it will soon be forgotten by people.
The following year in autumn, which was 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" as the final analysis book, just like their same-age peers, they confidently rejected this book.
Let's fast forward to the spring of 2007.
Several years after shelving the course, I taught "American Bestsellers" again.
When students chose their final analysis books, they chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone".
While I am preparing to accept their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, and when they first read J.K. Rowling's work, they were not yet university students, but were only in their early teens, just stepping into their teenage years. This means they grew up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione's companionship.
The same thing happened again in the autumn of 2010.
For these students, "we are growing up with Harry Potter" has become a motto rather than a label.
Will Harry disappear from memory?
As long as we are still alive, it is impossible.
Since 2010, I have taught bestseller courses twice, and both times students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final review.
Are you tired of Porter?
Based on the reviews of Harry Potter series on my other course, "Children's Literature," it doesn't seem very likely.
Now, I have chosen to include one Harry Potter novel in the curriculum, but I didn't choose Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone; instead, I chose Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban — — it's my favorite among the seven novels in the Harry Potter series, marking the series' transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, with intricate portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and mercy.
Many of my students also like this book the most.
How long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I give a lecture on children's literature, I always conduct a poll first: "Which of the books listed on the outline did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban".
In 2012, this figure rose to 94 %.
However, in the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline —— 87% in 2014, and dropped to 81% in 2016.
These are all not science, I know.
But I'm curious: will the ratio of students who have read Harry Potter drop to below 80% when I teach "Children's Literature" again next spring?
Will facts prove that students in 1999-2000 were right, that Harry Potter's position is consistently declining and will never be an eternal classic?
Is there still a balance point ahead, where the percentage remains stable and does not continue to decline?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I was very happy to have him enter my classroom all the time.
